    <main><div class='container-fluid' id='dict_container'>
      <h1><span class='badge badge-primary'>error handling in Go</span></h1>
      <div class='container-fluid'>
          <pre id='word_content' style='white-space: pre-wrap;'>Go provides a pretty simple error handling framework with inbuilt error interface type of the following declaration,
```
type error interface {
   Error() string
}
```
Functions normally return error as last return value. Use errors.New to construct a basic error message.
```
func Sqrt(value float64)(float64, error) {
   if(value &lt; 0){
      return 0, errors.New(&quot;Math: negative number passed to Sqrt&quot;)
   }
   return math.Sqrt(value), nil
}
```
Use return value and error message.
```
result, err:= Sqrt(-1)
if err != nil {
   fmt.Println(err)
}
```</pre>
      </div>
